text: what's up guys I am back home in the USA
after eight months of non-stop travel
since I was last here I've been to 11
countries in Asia ten in Africa and good
in culture here in Equatorial Guinea
eight in the Pacific Islands and three
in the Middle East I love being back
home it's like hitting the refresh
button on life I can get anything I need
at my favorite stores it's great to see
family and catch up with friends and eat
the foods that I've been missing for all
this time but to be honest I kind of
feel out of place in my own culture I
somehow feel more comfortable being in a
remote village in Gabon or driving
across Afghanistan than being in Las
Vegas right now a city that I lived in
for six years as a kid okay so this is
our old house in Henderson Nevada in the
90s what I'm feeling right now is called
reverse culture shock and it's stronger
than any regular culture shock I've ever
had I can't help but analyze everything
around me the plastic waste the sports
obsession the strip malls strip malls
that go on forever things are big in
America the cars the buildings the food
portions the people and everyone is so
open not that it's a bad thing at all
but complete strangers will talk to you
even if you don't know them I also find
it weird that everyone can speak English
around me because I'm so used to hearing
other languages for some reason I get
shy and introverted when people can
understand me but after living this life
for the last seven years I've gotten
pretty used to reverse culture shock and
it's not such a bad thing it just means
that I've been having amazing
experiences all over the world and it's
time to take a break and enjoy my
homeland for a few weeks I'll end this
video with a quote from the great Nelson
Mandela there is nothing like returning
to a place that remains unchanged to
find the ways in which you yourself have
altered alright guys that's it for me
we'll see you tomorrow from I'm so tired
